<h1>Bohr radius</h1>
<br />
<p><a href="http://en.citizendium.org/wiki/Niels_Bohr">Bohr</a>'s theory of the 
    <a href="http://en.citizendium.org/wiki/Hydrogen">hydrogen</a> atom (1913) predicts the existence of a 
    smallest orbit for the <a href="http://en.citizendium.org/wiki/Electron">electron</a> circulating the hydrogen 
    <a href="http://en.citizendium.org/wiki/Nucleus">nucleus</a>. Today the radius of this orbit is
    called the <strong>Bohr radius</strong>. It is usually indicated by <em>a</em><sub><span style="font-size: small;">0</span></sub></p>
<p>
    In the old quantum theory of Bohr and <a href="http://en.citizendium.org/wiki?title=Arnold_Sommerfeld&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1">Arnold Sommerfeld</a>
    , as well as in the new quantum theory of <a href="http://en.citizendium.org/wiki?title=Werner_Heisenberg&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1">Werner Heisenberg</a> 
    and <a href="http://en.citizendium.org/wiki?title=Erwin_Schr%C3%B6dinger&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1">Erwin Schr&ouml;dinger</a> the radius is given by
</p>

